Voter Data CVR Washoe

To replicate results:

Load libraries in the console:

library(dplyr)
library(tidyverse)
library(ggplot2)

First in the console, import the datafile 2024cvr. Then (also in the console) create a new, identical dataset cvr

cvr <- X2024cvr

Are there any identical entries in the dataset?

#this chunk counts how many votes have an identical entry
data_check <- cvr %>%
  group_by_all() %>%
  tally(name = "count") %>%
  filter(count > 1)

# Display the number of votes that have an identical entry
print(nrow(data_check))
[1] 0

There are no identical entries in the dataset.

To analyze voting patterns, we remove every column besides the actual voting data and run an analysis to show how many patterns have duplicates.

  group_by_all() %>%
  tally(name = "count") %>%
  filter(count == 1)

[1] 53893

#this chunk counts how many voting patterns have at least more than one duplicate
unique_votes_one <- votingcolumns %>%
  group_by_all() %>%
  tally(name = "count") %>%
  filter(count > 1)

# Display the number of unique voting patterns that have one duplicate or more
print(nrow(unique_votes_one))
[1] 4302
# Find voting patterns with at least more than two duplicates
unique_votes_more <- votingcolumns %>%
  group_by_all() %>%
  tally(name = "count") %>%
  filter(count > 2)

# Display the number of unique voting patterns that have more than two duplicates
print(nrow(unique_votes_more))
[1] 2170

There are 53,893 voting patterns across all precincts that do not have a duplicate.

2,132 voting patterns across all precincts have one duplicate.

2,170 voting patterns across all precincts have more than one duplicate.

There are several reasons why two people can have identical ballot
patterns:

Random Chance: In elections where candidates are listed in a random
order or where options are chosen randomly (like in some lotteries or
local elections), individuals can have identical ballot patterns purely
by chance.

Limited Choices: In elections with a limited number of candidates or
options, especially in smaller or local elections, the ballot choices
may be more constrained, increasing the likelihood of identical
patterns.

Similar Preferences: Voters with similar political or social views may
independently arrive at the same choices when presented with similar
candidates or issues on the ballot.

Influence of Campaigns or Media: Voter decisions can be influenced by
similar campaign messaging, media coverage, or public opinion, leading
to identical voting patterns among groups of voters.

Voter Guides or Recommendations: Voters may consult the same voter
guides, endorsements, or recommendations from trusted sources, resulting
in similar ballot selections.

Strategic Voting: In some cases, voters may strategically choose
candidates based on perceived electability or other strategic
considerations, leading to similar ballot patterns.

These factors can contribute to the occurrence of identical ballot
patterns among different voters, even in diverse electoral contexts.

Now lets see how those numbers change when we add precinct data.

The greatest number of duplicate voting patterns are in Sparks 6308 with 67/691 voting patterns.

Having 67 out of 691 voters in one precinct with the same voting pattern can depend on specific factors related to the election, the precinct, and the voting patterns themselves:

Type of Election: The type of election (local, state, national) and the nature of the candidates or issues involved can influence voting patterns. In elections with fewer candidates or more polarizing issues, it might be more common to see clusters of voters with similar patterns.

Demographics: The demographics of the precinct, including factors such as age, socioeconomic status, education level, and cultural background, can influence voting behavior. Similar demographic profiles among voters might lead to more uniform voting patterns.

Campaign Dynamics: Effective campaigning or issues that resonate strongly with voters in that precinct could lead to a higher degree of similarity in voting patterns.

Historical Context: Comparing the current elections voting patterns with past elections in the same precinct or similar elections elsewhere can provide context for understanding whether the observed patterns are typical or unusual.

Random Chance: While less likely with larger sample sizes, random chance can still play a role, particularly if there are fewer options on the ballot or if voters make decisions independently but coincidentally arrive at the same choices.

Keep Sparks 6308 in mind when looking at the next section of data.

In a graph, it looks like this:

Keep in mind that the count labels for Mail on the y axis is different from the Early Voting and Election Day counts!

library(ggplot2)

# Create separate plots faceted by CountingGroup
ggplot(comparison_table, aes(x = PrecinctPortion)) +
  geom_bar(aes(y = count_duplicates), stat = "identity", fill = "blue", alpha = 0.7) +
  geom_bar(aes(y = count_all), stat = "identity", fill = "orange", alpha = 0.7) +
  facet_wrap(~ CountingGroup, scales = "free") +
  labs(title = "Comparison of Top Counts by Counting Group",
       x = "Precinct",
       y = "Count") +
  theme_minimal() + 
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1))  # Rotate labels by 45 degrees

To simplify understanding of the data, look at the difference and ratio of the duplicates to all counts.


# Calculate differences
comparison_table$Difference <- comparison_table$count_all - comparison_table$count_duplicates

# Calculate ratios (assuming Count2 is not zero)
comparison_table$Ratio <- comparison_table$count_duplicates / comparison_table$count_all

# Arrange by smallest difference
comparison_table <- comparison_table %>%
  arrange(Difference)

# Display the updated dataset
#print(comparison_table)

# Split the data by CountingGroup
split_data_table2 <- split(comparison_table, comparison_table$CountingGroup)

# Print tables for each CountingGroup sorted by count in descending order
for (group in names(split_data_table2)) {
  cat("\nCounting Group:", group, "\n")
  sorted_table <- split_data_table2[[group]] %>%
    arrange(desc(Ratio))  # Sort by count column in descending order
  print(sorted_table)
  cat("\n")
}

# Calculate proportion of DuplicateCount to TotalCount for each PrecinctPortion and CountingGroup
data_re_analysis <- data_re %>%
  group_by(PrecinctPortion, CountingGroup) %>%
  summarise(
    Proportion = sum(count_duplicates) / sum(count_all)
  )
`summarise()` has grouped output by 'PrecinctPortion'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.
data_re_mail <- data_re_analysis %>%
  filter(CountingGroup == "Mail") %>%
  arrange(desc(Proportion))
data_re_electionday <- data_re_analysis %>%
  filter(CountingGroup == "Election Day") %>%
  arrange(desc(Proportion))
data_re_early <- data_re_analysis %>%
  filter(CountingGroup == "Early Voting") %>%
  arrange(desc(Proportion))

# Define a threshold for significant difference
# this is an arbitrary threshold, replace with a true number
# this threshold looks at differences greater than 10%
threshold <- 0.1

# Create a function to check for significant differences
check_difference <- function(re, de, threshold) {
  differences <- abs(re - de) > threshold
  return(differences)
}

# Apply the function to the joined data and filter for significant differences
significant_differences_rede_mail <- joined_rede_data_mail %>%
  rowwise() %>%
  mutate(SignificantDifference = check_difference(proportion_re_mail, proportion_de_mail, threshold)) %>%
  filter(SignificantDifference == TRUE)

# Print the filtered data with significant differences
print(significant_differences_rede_mail)

Out of 170 possible precincts, only 3 precincts had a proportion of duplicate voting patterns that were significantly different between republican and democrat mail-in ballots. That is 12.19% of all precincts.

Keep in mind: In local and state elections, the level of variation in voting patterns can vary based on several factors:

Candidate Diversity: If there are multiple candidates running within the party, voters may exhibit varying degrees of preference based on candidate qualifications, policies, or personal connections.

Issues at Stake: The importance and nature of the issues being addressed in the election can influence voting patterns. Voters may prioritize different aspects of the partys platform or agenda.

Campaign Dynamics: The effectiveness of candidate campaigns, endorsements, and outreach efforts can influence voter decisions. Strong campaigns may lead to more cohesive voting patterns, while weaker campaigns may result in more varied outcomes.

Demographics: The demographic composition of the electorate within the party can play a role. Different age groups, socioeconomic backgrounds, and geographic locations may have varying priorities and voting behaviors.

Party Unity: The level of unity or division within the party itself can impact voting patterns. In cases where the party is deeply divided on certain issues or candidates, there may be more variability in voting choices.

Historical Context: Previous election results and historical voting patterns within the party can provide context for understanding typical levels of variation. Changes in voter sentiment or party dynamics over time can also influence variation.

Typically, in local elections within one party, some level of variation in voting patterns is expected due to the diversity of opinions, preferences, and individual considerations among voters. However, the extent of this variation can vary widely depending on the specific circumstances of the election, including the factors mentioned above. Analyzing past election results and conducting voter surveys or focus groups can provide further insights into the typical variation expected in such elections.

The numbers demonstrate normal variation and a normal amount of duplicate voting patterns given the circumstances of the election.

# Example assuming some structure similar to your dataset

subset_undervote_cvr <- subset_cvr

# Example assuming some structure similar to your dataset
# Replace column names and types as per your actual dataset structure

# Clean and count undervotes
undervotes_count <- sapply(subset_undervote_cvr[, -(1:2)], function(x) {
  # Convert to character to handle factors
  x <- as.character(x)
  
  # Remove any non-numeric characters and convert to numeric
  x <- as.numeric(gsub("[^0-9.-]", "", x))  # Remove non-numeric characters
  
  # Count undervotes (excluding NA values)
  sum(x == 0 & !is.na(x))
})
